{"_id":"a4b12f70-318c-11eb-8b9d-8d0271819a2c","postId":"2015_04_a-tour-of-task-part-10-promise-tasks-76cdd5a7-1909-3432-9e00-8acd3cd4350c","postUri":"https://blog.stephencleary.com/2015/04/a-tour-of-task-part-10-promise-tasks.html","replyTo":"e03b6990-318a-11eb-8b9d-8d0271819a2c","authorEmailEncrypted":"","authorEmailMD5":"23448e78d187fba56d8bc263081ac5d8","authorName":"Stephen Cleary","authorUri":"https://stephencleary.com","message":"`Task.Yield` isn't quite as bad. `Task.Run` takes another thread, and then yield the current thread. `Task.Yield` would yield the current thread and then take a thread (which may be the same thread).\r\n\r\nThat said, I can't think of any reason to use `Task.Yield` on ASP.NET, either. It's still reducing the efficiency of the application while providing no benefit, just like `Task.Run`.","date":"2020-11-28T15:16:09.542Z"}